## UX Review: Music Lessons Monorepo (sarah-practice-plan + music-chart)

### Summary
- Critical Issues: 4
- Major Issues: 9
- Minor Issues: 11
- Accessibility Issues: 8
- Overall UX Score: 6.5 / 10

Both apps share strong visual design DNA and genuine craft in their interaction patterns. The issues are concentrated in three areas: near-total absence of ARIA semantics, a navigation split that creates cognitive overhead for the target user (a single musician), and a small number of interaction gaps that would cause real friction during active practice sessions.

---

## Critical Issues

### [UX-001] No `aria-label` on any navigation button — screen readers receive only icon names
- **Heuristic:** #4 Consistency and Standards / WCAG 4.1.2
- **Apps:** Both
- **Location:** `sarah-practice-plan/src/App.jsx` line 4149 — `BottomNav`; `music-chart/src/components/BottomNav.jsx` line 8
- **Issue:** Every `<button>` in both bottom navigation bars renders only a Lucide icon and a bare `<span className="nav-label">`. The icon itself has no `aria-label` and the Lucide SVG does not carry accessible text. A screen reader announces "Music Practice" / "Sparkles Skills" etc. because it reads the SVG title (browser-dependent and inconsistent), or reads only the label text. More critically, the _active state_ is communicated only by CSS class and color (`#d4a373` gold). There is no `aria-current="page"` on the active item.
- **Impact:** Screen reader users cannot reliably navigate between the four primary tabs. The active-state color alone fails WCAG 1.4.1 (use of color as sole differentiator).
- **Fix:**
  ```jsx
  <button
    className={`nav-item ${tab === "practice" ? "active" : ""}`}
    onClick={() => setTab("practice")}
    aria-label="Practice tab"
    aria-current={tab === "practice" ? "page" : undefined}
  >
  ```
  Add `aria-hidden="true"` to the Lucide icon so the text label is the sole announced name.

---

### [UX-002] `outline: none` on all buttons and inputs — keyboard focus is invisible
- **Heuristic:** #6 Recognition Rather Than Recall / WCAG 2.4.7 (Focus Visible, Level AA)
- **Apps:** Both
- **Location:** `sarah-practice-plan/src/index.css` line 22; `music-chart/src/index.css` line 22; plus explicit `outline: "none"` on individual inputs at `music-chart/src/charts/StrumChartBuilder.jsx` lines 829, 1003, 1133, 1548
- **Issue:** Both `index.css` files globally reset `button { outline: none; }`. While `music-chart/src/App.css` defines a `.counter:focus-visible` rule, that class is only on the Vite boilerplate counter component — it is never applied to any of the app's actual interactive elements. Every button, range slider, and text input is invisible to keyboard users when focused.
- **Impact:** The app is entirely non-navigable by keyboard. Any musician who uses a keyboard with a tablet stand (common practice setup) has no visual affordance for focus state. This is a WCAG Level AA failure.
- **Fix:** Replace the global `outline: none` reset with a `:focus-visible` override that provides a visible ring:
  ```css
  button:focus-visible,
  input:focus-visible,
  [tabindex]:focus-visible {
    outline: 2px solid #d4a373; /* T.gold */
    outline-offset: 2px;
  }
  button { outline: none; } /* only suppress on non-keyboard interaction */
  ```

