### [UX-003] Flow Mode swipe gesture conflicts with browser back gesture and scroll
- **Heuristic:** #3 User Control and Freedom / #5 Error Prevention
- **App:** sarah-practice-plan
- **Location:** `App.jsx` lines 1285–1303 (`onTouchStart` / `onTouchEnd` in `FlowMode`)
- **Issue:** The swipe-left / swipe-right gesture to navigate between exercises in Flow Mode uses a threshold of `Math.abs(dx) < 80 || Math.abs(dx) < Math.abs(dy) * 2`. On iOS, the system-level back-swipe gesture triggers from the left edge at exactly this distance range. Users attempting to go back to the previous exercise routinely trigger a browser navigation instead of an in-app exercise change. Additionally, the gesture is completely undiscoverable — there is no visual affordance (no "swipe" hint, no edge indicator, no instructional text).
- **Impact:** Users either accidentally exit the app entirely, or never discover the swipe feature exists. The only visible navigation is the progress rail dots (8–12px tap targets, well below the 44px minimum).
- **Fix:** Add `touch-action: pan-y` CSS to the Flow container so horizontal swipes are handled by the app but vertical scrolling by the browser. Provide a visible hint on first launch. Ensure the progress rail dots are wrapped in a button with `min-width: 44px; min-height: 44px` with the visual dot centered inside.

